	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Revisions to the EU Generalised System of Preferences </h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The reforms to the GSP proposed by the European Commission in May 2011 will mainly affect trade in agricultural and fisheries products and benefit richer states, according to a new study published by ODI. The reform proposal was made in May 2011 for discussion with the EU member states and the European Parliament in the expectation that it will come into force in 2014 (when the current regime will expire). Its main features have been widely discussed and summarised in an issue of ICTSD’s <i>Trade Negotiations Insights</i>. But, because the proposal only sets out the criteria and formulae to be applied in the new regime, an understanding of how it may affect relative ACP market access for agricultural and fisheries goods has had to await the completion of independent research, which is now starting to be published.</p><p>The EC proposal includes some examples of how GSP beneficiaries will be affected, but these are only illustrations. The Commission has also published an impact assessment, but none of the scenarios appear to equate exactly to the new proposals. The Commission intends to make the real calculations on who gains and who loses shortly before the new regime becomes effective, enabling it to use the most up to date information available at that time.</p><p>Some changes will reduce GSP benefits. Over half of current beneficiaries will become ineligible for the GSP if:</p>
<ul>

<li>they are dependencies of an EU state; </li>

<li>they have an FTA with the EU; </li>

<li>or they are too rich, having ‘been classified by the World Bank as a high-income country or UMIC during three consecutive years immediately preceding the update of the list of beneficiary countries’ (Article 4.1.a). </li>

</ul>
<p>This will have a knock-on effect on what is known as ‘product graduation’, under which countries lose GSP for a group of goods when they exceed a set threshold of EU imports from all GSP states. The threshold will be increased, but as a share of imports from less than half the number of states currently included – so more states will be graduated on more products.</p><p>Other changes may increase benefits for some states. Countries eligible for the GSP+ scheme (which gives deeper preferences on more goods than the standard regime) will no longer be subject to product graduation. The eligibility criteria will also change. GSP+ is granted only to states defined as ‘vulnerable’ that are implementing specified core international human, labour and environmental standards and with respect to good governance. The Commission proposes to ‘tweak’, or adapt, the vulnerability criterion so that some ineligible states, such as Pakistan, become potentially eligible. But this depends on whether they also fulfil the other conditions, and the proposal contains no illustrations of potential beneficiaries.</p><p>The Commission argues that the changes will ‘focus the GSP preferences on the countries most in need’. However the first two independent research reports, published recently by CARIS at the University of Sussex and ODI, suggest that this is unlikely. ODI finds that the main beneficiaries of any shift in import patterns as a result of graduation will be rich and higher middle income states. This is partly because many of the affected goods will be agricultural and fishery items that poor states cannot produce. CARIS estimates that any significant gains from the reforms are most likely to accrue to states that become eligible for GSP+.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>EC, ‘Proposal for a Regulation of the European Parliament and of the Council applying a scheme of generalised tariff preferences’, COM(2011) 241 final, 2011/0117 (COD), 10 May 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2011/may/tradoc_147893.pdf" target="_self">http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2011/may/tradoc_147893.pdf</a></p><p>EC, ‘Impact assessment Vol. 1, Commission Staff Working Paper, SEC (2011) 536 final, 10 May 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/governance/impact/ia_carried_out/docs/ia_2011/sec_2011_0536_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/governance/impact/ia_carried_out/docs/ia_2011/sec_20...</a></p><p>ECDPM, <i>Trade Negotiations </i><i>Insights</i>, Issue 5, Volume 10<b>&nbsp;, </b>July–August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/index.php?loc=tni/" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/index.php?loc=tni/</a></p><p>Centre for the Analysis of Regional Integration at Sussex/TradeSift, ‘A preliminary investigation into the effects of the changes in the EU’s GSP’, 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tradesift.com/Reports/GSP_Report_June2011.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.tradesift.com/Reports/GSP_Report_June2011.pdf</a></p><p>ODI, ‘The poverty impact of the proposed graduation threshold in the Generalised System of Preferences (GSP) trade scheme’, by C. Stevens, K. Bird, J. Keane, J. Kennan, D.W. te Velde, and K. Higgins, October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://bit.ly/odi-gsp-fullreport" target="_self">http://bit.ly/odi-gsp-fullreport</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The GSP reforms are of importance to the ACP from two perspectives: as potential beneficiaries of the scheme and as potential competitors. Given the Commission’s proposal to remove the autonomous preferences available to countries still negotiating EPAs (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/EPAs/EC-proposes-January-2014-as-deadline-for-completion-of-EPA-process" target="_blank">EC proposes January 2014 as deadline for completion of EPA process</a>’, November 2011) the potential beneficiaries include all ACP states that remain outside an EPA. LDCs will not be affected – the ‘Everything but arms’ (EBA) regime will remain unchanged. However, some non-LDCs could be subject to higher market access barriers. Namibia and Botswana, for example, face graduation out of the GSP altogether since both are classified as an Upper Middle Income Country, and Kenya will face new tariffs on several key exports.</p><p>The changes to GSP+ will tend to erode existing ACP preferences (under either EBA or an EPA), particularly if powerful competitors such as Pakistan become eligible.</p><p>Nor is it likely that this will be offset by gains on goods where strong competitors have been graduated. The ODI research suggests that gains will be tiny and focused on a few states, such as Senegal for fish and Kenya for green beans.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
